      <hedline>
        <hl1>Climate Lessons, Right From the Mountaintop</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Julie Downs letter on Oliver Morton's Nov 17 article calls for efforts to avert global warming and save Mount Kilimanjaro's glaciers; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>We need not idly sit by while our planet suffers permanent damage: Oliver Morton (Op-Ed, Nov. 17) suggests a plan to avert one casualty of global warming. If we can save the snows of Mount Kilimanjaro, we can do anything: Make fuel-efficient cars and mass transportation the state of the art.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>We need not idly sit by while our planet suffers permanent damage: Oliver Morton (Op-Ed, Nov. 17) suggests a plan to avert one casualty of global warming. If we can save the snows of Mount Kilimanjaro, we can do anything: Make fuel-efficient cars and mass transportation the state of the art.</p>
        <p>Turn polluting, inhumane, profit-minded factory farms back into small, ecologically sound family farms. Make businesses pay for the pollution they create, so that polluting will no longer pay.</p>
        <p>I, for one, hereby volunteer to help drape tarps over the ice cliffs of Kilimanjaro, as a symbolic (and practical) act toward saving the planet. I hope that our legislators can follow suit.</p>
        <p>JULIE DOWNS  Pittsburgh, Nov. 17, 2003</p>
      </block>
